            <div id="stability" class="tab-pane">
                <h2>Organizational Stability Index (OSI) & Key Events</h2>
                <p>The OSI is a proprietary, blended metric combining factors like Executive Tenure, Key Contract Wins/Losses, Stock Performance Volatility, and Major Reorganization Frequency.</p>

                <div class="org-stability">
                    <div>
                        <h3>Booz Allen Hamilton OSI (Internal Score)</h3>
                        <span class="stability-score">8.5 / 10</span>
                        <p><strong>Rationale:</strong> High executive tenure (Rozanski since 2014), strong pipeline ($12B+ RPO), but a slight reduction due to a major HQ relocation announcement and competitive contract protest activity.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div>
                        <h3>Competitor Comparison (Simulated OSI)</h3>
                        <ul class="competitor-list">
                            <li><strong>Leidos:</strong> 7.8/10 (High Revenue, but continuous large M&A integrations can introduce short-term instability.)</li>
                            <li><strong>SAIC:</strong> 7.0/10 (Recent M&A activity and potential contract shifts add minor volatility.)</li>
                            <li><strong>CACI:</strong> 8.2/10 (Strong contract wins (e.g., NSA FocusedFox) and technology focus provide solid stability.)</li>
                        </ul>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <h2 style="margin-top: 40px;">Key Events (Last 3 Years)</h2>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Acquisition of EverWatch (2022):</strong> Significant move to bolster **National Security** capabilities, particularly in cyber and intelligence services, successfully clearing a DOJ antitrust challenge.</li>
                    <li><strong>NSA FocusedFox Contract Protest (2023):</strong> BAH and Leidos protested the $2.4B NSA contract awarded to CACI, highlighting intense competition for major, high-value intelligence community work.</li>
                    <li><strong>Strategic Shift to Velocity/VoC:</strong> Continued emphasis on the **Velocity/Value of Content (VoC)** business strategy to accelerate growth in high-demand, advanced technology services (AI, 5G, Cyber).</li>
                </ul>
            </div>

            <div id="comp-analysis" class="tab-pane">
                <h2>Strengths, Weaknesses, and Competitive Comparison</h2>

                <table class="comp-table">
                    <thead>
                        <tr>
                            <th>Category</th>
                            <th>Booz Allen Hamilton (BAH)</th>
                            <th>Competitive Landscape (SAIC, Leidos, CACI)</th>
                        </tr>
                    </thead>
                    <tbody>
                        <tr>
                            <td class="strength">STRENGTHS</td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong class="strength">Deep Government Penetration:</strong> Decades-long, deep relationships across **all US Intelligence and Defense agencies**.</li>
                                    <li><strong class="strength">Technology Leadership:</strong> Recognized lead in **Cybersecurity and AI/Data Science** solutions tailored for government mission-critical needs.</li>
                                    <li><strong class="strength">Talent Base:</strong> Reputation for high number of personnel with top-tier security clearances (**TS/SCI**).</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Leidos:</strong> Greater scale in large IT infrastructure/hardware integration (closer to a traditional defense contractor).</li>
                                    <li><strong>CACI:</strong> Exceptional agility and focus on proprietary technology/products, particularly in the Intelligence community.</li>
                                    <li><strong>SAIC:</strong> Strong presence in logistics, platform integration, and broader IT modernization.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                            <td class="weakness">WEAKNESSES</td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong class="weakness">Revenue Concentration:</strong> Heavily reliant on the **U.S. Federal Government** (near 97% of revenue), making it highly sensitive to budget cycles and legislative changes.</li>
                                    <li><strong class="weakness">Consulting Legacy:</strong> Historically perceived as a "staff augmentation" firm, despite the strong pivot to technology, which can hinder competition with pure-play tech integrators.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                            <td>
                                <ul>
                                    <li><strong>Leidos/SAIC:</strong> More diversified revenue streams outside of core Defense/Intelligence (e.g., Leidos in Civil/Health IT, SAIC in broader IT).</li>
                                    <li><strong>All:</strong> All competitors face similar **talent and wage inflation** challenges in the cleared personnel market.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </td>
                        </tr>
                    </tbody>
                </table>
